<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Ashdown hints at closer Labour links
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paddy Ashdown yesterday signalled his hopes that the Liberal Democrats
would provide the reforming edge in a post-election partnership with the
Labour party.
In a coded message to Labour leader Tony Blair, Mr Ashdown said the Liberal
Democrats had 'enough confidence in our own strength to make common cause
with others to achieve the best for the future'.
The government after the next election should be one in which the Liberal
Democrats provided key policies.
Addressing the party conference at Brighton, the Liberal Democrat leader
said the party's 'historic role' was to act as the catalyst for
constitutional change in Britain. That meant dismantling the 'centralised
state' and introducing proportional representation.
But Mr Ashdown (pictured with his wife, Jane, after his speech) ducked an
explicit offer of an anti-Tory pact and gave no details of his strategy to
secure closer co-operation with Labour.
Speech details and conference reports, Page 10
</TEXT>
