<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / World Stock Markets (America): US equities slip back as
pessimism prevails
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks extended their losses yesterday as pessimism over monetary policy
continued to dominate investment strategies, writes Frank McGurty in New
York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 17.49 lower at 3,851.60, having
recovered from a 47-point deficit at mid-afternoon. The more broadly based
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was down 1.9 at 461.46. Volume on the Big Board was
heavy, with 354m shares traded by the close.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite was 3.38 weaker at
454.77, and the Nasdaq composite was off 6.04 at 760.70.
Bargain hunters were in short supply at the opening, despite a 67-point
tumble by the Dow the previous session. Amid the current uncertainty over
interest rates, investors were unable to stem the losing tide.
On balance, the day's economic news was neutral for stocks. The commerce
department said August housing starts had risen by 2.1 per cent, surprising
analysts who were expecting a small decline. But economists later explained
away the increase as a reflection of activity in the multi-family sector.
Single-family starts, viewed as a more accurate barometer, were down last
month.
Equity investors again interpreted the data through its impact on bond
prices. Initially, the announcement of the headline figure send Treasuries
into retreat. Stocks took the bait and plunged.
After the data had been interpreted, bonds quickly pulled back to within a
few ticks of their starting point. The Dow industrials followed suit.
By early afternoon, however, the blue chip index was still showing solid
losses, as investors tried to calculate the odds on whether the Federal
Reserve policy would remain on hold until after the November elections.
Mr Wayne Angell, chief economist for Bear Stearns and a former Fed governor,
came out on the side of those betting on an early move, saying there was a
60 per cent chance the central bank would decide to tighten at its September
27 policy meeting.
With such speculation afoot, the market's negative tone would not budge. The
Dow industrials plunged anew, only to retrace their steps for a second time.
By the close, Caterpillar had slipped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 54 1/8 ,
Kodak fell Dollars 1 to Dollars 51 3/4 and General Motors dropped Dollars
1/8 to Dollars 48 5/8 . The session's biggest loser was Maybelline, whose
share prices plunged 24 per cent, or Dollars 5 7/8 to Dollars 18 3/4 .
Banco Wiese climbed Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 22 7/8 in its debut session. It
become the first Peruvian stock to be listed on the NYSE with its IPO of
2.4m shares.
On the Nasdaq, Lotus Development led the technology sector's slide. The
stock fell Dollars 1 to Dollars 39 1/2 after Mr Timothy McCollum, an analyst
at Dean Witter Reynolds, warned that lacklustre European sales could depress
third-quarter results.
Canada
Toronto prices staged a late-session rally, but still closed lower in
moderate trading, as the Toronto market once again followed the lead of its
slumping counterpart in New York.
The TSE 300 composite index fell 18.25 points, or 0.42 per cent, to close at
4,358.62. Volume was 62.22m shares down from Tuesday's 65.58m, but trading
value rose to CDollars 976.8m from CDollars 973.1m.
Brazil
Sao Paulo stocks rallied as Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso's running mate
appeared to be absolved of responsibility in an alleged kickback scheme, to
which news reports had linked him.
The exchange gained 1,662 points, or 3.2 per cent, to 53,435 points on the
Bovespa Index, up from Tuesday's 51,773. The Rio de Janeiro Exchange gained
413 points, or 2.2 per cent, to 19,553 points on the BVRJ Index.
</TEXT>
