<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / International Company News: ENI rebound opens way for
privatisation options
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A strong return to profitability by ENI, the Italian state oil concern, has
opened the way for the Berlusconi government to look afresh on the various
options for privatisation.
Mr Franco Bernabe, ENI chief executive, told parliament yesterday the group
was heading for a L2,000bn (Dollars 1.28bn) net profit in 1994 with the bulk
of costly restructuring of loss-making sectors such as chemicals nearly
complete. He said this improved performance allowed the government to opt
for two separate paths in privatisation.
It could either be via the formation of a company grouping all the interests
with those still controlled by ENI. Alternatively, ENI could be split into
three - energy, chemicals, and other activities - that would be owned
directly by the state. ENI, on its L50,000bn annual turnover, is the sixth
largest oil group in the world.
The government has been sitting on earlier proposals put forward by Mr
Bernabe which were in line with guidelines laid down by the previous Amato
and Ciampi governments that envisaged the creation of a 'super-Agip' centred
round the core of the group, Agip, the producer of oil and gas. Mr Bernabe
appears determined to force the government into deciding a clear policy for
the group. However, the government is far from united with the neo-fascist
MSI/National Alliance resisting large-scale privatisation.
On ENI's performance, the improved profit projection against a mere L419m in
1993 in part is attributed to extraordinary items from continuing
divestments. Through August, ENI had raised L1,776bn from 60 new assets
sales. The burden on the consolidated balance sheet continues to come at
least for this year from the chemicals side which lost L2,600bn in 1993 and
which accounts for only 15 per cent of turnover.
Mr Bernabe said that if ENI's energy interests were hived off, it could
remain in charge of running the privatisation of the other activities. But
he clearly outlined his preference by pointing to the creation of strong
state-dominated energy holdings with private stakes like Spain's creation of
Repsol from INH.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Ente Nazionale Idrocarburi.
</CO>
<XX>
