<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / International Company News: A long haul for Credit Lyonnais
 -David Buchan explains why the heavy losses will continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is still light at the end of the tunnel for Credit Lyonnais, Mr Jean
Peyrelevade believes, but the tunnel is proving far longer than he thought
when he took over as chairman of the state-controlled bank nearly a year
ago.
Credit Lyonnais will today announce a hefty first-half net loss after
provisions. Last year the bank reported a full year loss of FFr6.9bn
(Dollars 1.3bn).
In the first six months of 1994, Credit Lyonnais suffered from the decline
in the demand for bank loans by France's cash-rich companies, but also saw
its profits from trading on more depressed capital markets fall sharply.
At the same time, Credit Lyonnais still reckons it must maintain a high
level of provisions throughout this year to clean up its messy past.
One result is an inevitable delay to the further capital increase that
Credit Lyonnais needs, beyond the FFr4.9bn that it got in July from the
state, the state-owned Thomson electronics group and the Caisse des Depots
bank, which together make up 80 per cent of its capital.
At 8.3 per cent, Credit Lyonnais's solvency ratio is in need of further
strengthening.
Committed to public spending rigour, the Balladur government has no means to
buttress the bank's capital any further, and has told Credit Lyonnais that
it can tap the stock market any time before the full privatisation expected
in the late 1990s.
But realistically, the bank realises it has no chance of attracting
investors until next year, when it hopes for strong expansion in the French
economy and the start of the turnaround in its own finances.
Provisions against bad risks and loans are clearly the main millstone around
the neck of Credit Lyonnais.
For last year, Mr Peyrelevade set aside a total of FFr17.8bn, with just over
half of this considered normal provisions on 'current' banking business and
the rest 'exceptional' measures to compensate for precautions which the
previous regime of Mr Jean-Yves Haberer should have taken earlier,
particularly in non-traditional banking activities such as investments in
industry, property development and cinema.
It is clear, however, that both categories of provision will remain high
this year. The bank says this is not because it has uncovered any new real
horrors, but is mainly because its branch managers have decided to take
advantage of the 'big sweep-out' to make a clean breast of all past problems
as well as to be far more cautious on new business. This has been welcomed,
even encouraged, by the bank's new auditors.
By contrast, the French Treasury has not been totally enthusiastic about
continued high provisions, wiping out hope of any dividend for the state and
maintaining the question mark over how it let Credit Lyonnais get into such
bad shape in the first place. But after a parliamentary inquiry's critical
conclusions about their competence, or lack of it, the Treasury has been
ill-placed to oppose Mr Peyrelevade's stringency.
This stringency has uncovered further problems, and need for provisions, in
the group's Althus and Societe de Banque Occidentale (SDBO) subsidiaries.
It was the proud boast of the high-rolling Mr Jean-Francois Henin that when
he ran Althus from 1990-93 he multiplied its balance sheet many times over
but never increased its staff.
The upshot was a chaotic back office, out of which dubious dossiers are
still emerging. SDBO was the vehicle for loans to Mr Bernard Tapie. After
all the fuss it made in mortgaging and eventually seizing the
politician-tycoon's valuables, Credit Lyonnais has discovered this summer
that Mr Tapie's art and furniture are only worth perhaps a tenth of the
FFr350m the bank was counting on.
The one shaft of light penetrating the tunnel so far is that growth in the
group's operating costs and depreciation which was 4.1 per cent last year
has been kept close to zero this year.
Mr Peyrelevade has frozen his own salary and those of his top two dozen
lieutenants, and is cutting 1,100 banking jobs in France and a further 900
in Europe over the current year.
This is part of the two-pronged strategy to:
Improve profitability and efficiency in the core banking business.
Measures already announced include closure of some UK retail branches to
focus more on corporate banking and market trading there, and new
centralised management of European banking and foreign exchange trading
worldwide.
Sell FFr20bn worth of non-core industrial participations in 1994-95.
This programme is on track, and so far FFr6bn worth of assets have been
sold. They include big stakes in the Fnac record and book chain, the UAF
life insurance company (with Credit Lyonnais still retaining the majority),
the Essilor spectacle lens company, and the TF1 television station.
Credit Lyonnais is now said to want to sell its 10 per cent stake in the
Meridien hotel chain to Forte, the UK group which is buying control of
Meridien from Air France.
Even though the eventual plan is for Credit Lyonnais to keep some FFr30bn
worth of industrial holdings, for the moment 'anything that is outside
banking is, in principle, sellable,' says one bank executive.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Credit Lyonnais.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
