<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / UK Company News: Fluctuating milk prices behind Golden
Vale's fall to IPounds 4.4m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CAROLINE SOUTHEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fluctuations in milk prices led to a 52 per cent drop in pre-tax profits at
Golden Vale, the Irish diary group, although acquisitions lifted turnover at
the interim stage.
In the six months to June 30, pre-tax profits fell from IPounds 9.14m to
IPounds 4.43m (Pounds 4.37m). Operating profits fell from IPounds 10.03m to
IPounds 6.61m, which included a reorganisation charge of Pounds 1.52m.
Turnover increased by 39 per cent from IPounds 184.5m to IPounds 256.1m,
including a IPounds 77.9m contribution from acquisitions.
Sales in the dairy and food products division were down from IPounds 164m to
IPounds 154.6m.
Mr Jim O'Mahony, chief executive, reiterated a warning first issued in June
that pre-tax profits for the full year would fall by a third.
The share price, which shed 30 per cent after the first profits warning,
closed up 2p at 57p yesterday.
The fall in profits was caused by a number of factors, he said. The
imbalance between the price paid to suppliers for milk and the market price
of products caused a IPounds 2m drop in the contribution to operating
profits from milk.
However, production efficiencies and improved margins produced a IPounds
800,000 contribution from milk related products.
An unchanged interim dividend of 0.6p was declared. Earnings per share fell
from 4.66p to 2.3p.
</TEXT>
