<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / UK Company News: Malaya to acquire Heron dealership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Malaya Group, the USM-quoted motor distributor, has agreed terms in
principle to acquire Heron Motor Group, the motor dealership arm of Mr
Gerald Ronson's Heron group.
Industry sources suggest that the consideration will be about Pounds 16m.
Malaya's shares were suspended yesterday, pending a further announcement 'in
the next few weeks'. Mr Nick Lancaster, chief executive, said this was to
staunch rumours that had been circulating in the trade. He expected
completion at the end of October.
He added that the Stock Exchange was treating the deal as a reverse, because
until August 1992, when Mr Lancaster and a concert party bought into the
group, it had been virtually as hell. Mr Lancaster said that most of
Malaya's acquisitions took place in the second half of the last financial
year and the first eight months of this.
As a reverse takeover, the exchange has concerns over continuity of
management and it is understood this accounts for the delay. Malaya wants Mr
John Bradley, managing director of Heron Motor, to join the Malaya board.
Heron Motor includes the London-based businesses of HR Owen, HMG Bromley and
Stockport-based Hollingdrake. Turnover of the combined group is expected to
be about Pounds 150m-Pounds 160m, with Heron contributing some Pounds 90m.
The sale proceeds will help cut debt at Heron Corporation, a subsidiary of
Heron International, which is currently undergoing financial restructuring.
Under this, bondholders will receive no payment until the bank creditors of
Heron Corporation have been paid off.
</TEXT>
