FT  22 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is a good evening for 'pastime' programmes. At 8.00 BBC2 starts a new
six-part series of The Edge looking at the history of Scottish
mountaineering. At the same time C4 begins a repeat of Wildshots, a
five-part series in which photographer Chris Packham gives hints on wildlife
photography. That is followed by a new series of Screaming Reels, which is
not about horror movies but fishing (8.30). At the same moment BBC2 begins
another series of Top Gear, the highly successful series for motoring
freaks. In its Brando season C4 shows the 1952 movie Viva Zapata] in which
Marlon smoulders and snarls behind lots of face fungus. It is not a great
film, but Kazan directed from Steinbeck's script, and Anthony Quinn won an
Oscar in the role of Zapata's brother (10.00). Inside Story tells of the
lives of twins June and Jennifer Gibbons. As children they spoke only to one
another, though they seemed to have a love-hate relationship. Sent to
Broadmoor after a series of arson attacks, they were released in 1993
whereupon Jennifer stopped living, though she took no active steps to end
her life (10.00 BBC1).
