<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Cable TV service for City launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Videotron, the largest cable television operator in London, yesterday
launched what it described as the first public business multimedia service
in the UK.
The new television service will combine data, sound and pictures in as many
as 48 channels devoted to the business market and delivered to the personal
computers of subscribers in Westminster and the City.
The Westminster cable franchise is held by British Telecommunications but
the Department of Trade and Industry earlier this year awarded Videotron a
licence to offer competing telephony services to business and residential
customers in the area. The Canadian-owned cable group is now laying a Pounds
38m high-capacity fibre-optic network in Westminster and the City.
Videotron will compete for estimated average annual telecommunication
revenues within the City of Pounds 67.5m per sq km.
Unlike other telephone companies Videotron is also to offer television
services to the business market - although under its licence it cannot offer
general entertainment.
Early next year Reuters, the information and media group, will provide a
business news service for Videotron. There will probably be a two-hour
business programme and a similar programme towards the end of the business
day, plus a non-stop stream of prices and other data.
</TEXT>
