<DATE>940922
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / MP leads activist warning on Blair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ms Liz Lynne, the Liberal Democrat MP for Rochdale, yesterday put herself at
the head of a fringe group of the party which is unwilling to see any
rapprochement with Labour before the next election, James Blitz writes.
Amid deep divisions among Liberal Democrats over how they should approach Mr
Tony Blair, the new Labour leader, Ms Lynne told a fringe meeting at the
Brighton conference she was opposed to initiating talks between the parties.
Arguing that Labour remained dominated by old-style socialists, she said: 'I
don't think Tony Blair will be able to deliver. He hasn't put any flesh on
his policies.'
Her comments were warmly received by about 150 Liberal Democrat activists
attending a meeting of the Urban Campaign Network, which aims to co-ordinate
the Liberal Democrat campaign against Labour in inner-city areas.
The strong support shown for Ms Lynne will serve as a warning to Mr Paddy
Ashdown not to hint at a rapprochement with Labour in his keynote speech
today if he is to keep his party united.
The strong opposition towards Labour among Liberal Democrat councillors is
not shared by most of the parliamentary party.
</TEXT>
