<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Ashdown edges closer to Labour: Lib Dem leader sets PR as
price of any deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paddy Ashdown will today seek to nudge the Liberal Democrats further in
the direction of co-operation with Mr Tony Blair's Labour party by
suggesting that the two parties could build a bipartisan consensus on issues
such as the future of the National Health Service.
But, in an attempt to narrow Liberal Democrat divisions over his push for an
accommodation with Labour, he will use his closing speech to the party
conference to set the price for any formal deal between the two parties as a
Labour commitment to proportional representation.
His speech, previewed yesterday by senior aides, will attempt to walk a
tightrope - holding the door of co-operation open to Mr Blair while
reassuring his own party that the Liberal Democrats will not be 'rolled
over' in any discussions.
Mr Blair's reaction to the idea of cross-party collaboration on the health
service will be seen as a test of his commitment to what Mr Ashdown refers
to as a new style of pluralist politics.
The speech will follow indications yesterday from senior party figures that
the Liberal Democrats plan to counter the electoral threat from Labour by
focusing all their resources at the next general election on 70 or 80 seats
 -most of them Tory held - where they have a chance of winning.
But Mr Ashdown's attempts during a difficult and unpredictable Brighton
conference to hold open the door to Mr Blair were clouded when the new
Liberal Democrat party president launched a strong attack on the new Labour
leader.
Mr Robert Maclennan accused Mr Blair of reducing Labour to 'a sort of
smiling anaemia'. Mr Maclennan subsequently told journalists that he was
determined there should be no 'behind-the-scenes bargaining with Labour'.
Mr Ashdown, who is expected to chide the party conference gently for its
defiance of the party leadership in two conference votes, plans to use his
speech to set a series of 'benchmarks' against which the Liberal Democrats
can judge the prospects for a closer relationship with Labour.
But with the substantial anti-Labour group within his party threatening open
revolt against any formal alliance, Mr Ashdown will stress that support for
proportional representation would be the price he would demand for
supporting a future Labour government.
</TEXT>
