<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Fares discussion change rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A railway passengers' watchdog yesterday threw out a British Rail proposal
that up to 72 hours should be allowed for 'consultation' over fare changes.
The Central Rail Users' Consultative Committee rejected the BR plan at its
quarterly meeting on the grounds that 72 hours was not long enough for
genuine consultation. Its stand won the backing of the Office of the Rail
Regulator.
The committee, which brings together regional passenger committees, was
considering a draft proposal from BR on fares consultation.
Last year's legislation privatising BR gave the committee the right to be
consulted over fare changes.
Yesterday's move could force the train operating companies which take over
services from BR to involve local passenger committees at an earlier stage.
At present BR announces one set of fare changes a year, but monitoring fares
will become more complicated as the 25 train operators announce their own
tariffs.
Major-General Lennox Napier, committee chairman, said 72 hours 'amounts to
information, not consultation'.
Mr John Nelson, managing director of BR's south-eastern train operating
companies, said any proposal for a longer consultation period would have to
take into account the impact on the train operators' ability to manage their
businesses.
Maj-Gen Napier said the committee and BR needed to go 'back to the drawing
board' to look at the Railways Act in detail to produce a new proposal for
fares consultation.
</TEXT>
