<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Howard warns of fire pay reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, is considering introducing
performance-related pay into the fire service for those at assistant
divisional officer level.
In a move that seems likely to provoke widespread resistance, Mr Howard also
said he was looking at fixed-term appointments and considering whether these
might be introduced for chief fire officers.
Speaking yesterday to the Chief and Assistant Chief Fire Officers
Association conference, Mr Howard went on to say that he was concerned about
the growing cost of the firefighters' pension scheme.
He added that a review team would identify ways in which the benefits and
costs could be made more comparable to other public service schemes but gave
an assurance that existing pensioners would not be affected by any changes.
The home secretary's suggestions of change in pay determination is bound to
arouse widespread anxiety across the entire fire service.
Last year the Fire Brigades Union carried out a successful campaign in
defence of their national wage agreement. The agreement is based on a
17-year-old wage formula that links pay to the upper quartile of male manual
earnings.
Although most fire fighters would not be covered by what Mr Howard is
planning, union officials fear that any performance-related pay system and
fixed-term contracts would eventually have to be extended to their members.
The union has some members at assistant divisional officer level.
The home secretary told yesterday's conference that performance-related pay
could 'encourage greater efficiency in the public as well as the private
sector of the economy'. He added: 'It is an important element in the
results-oriented culture that is being developed in all our public
services.'
The planned shake-up of pay and working conditions in the fire service
follows the row that Mr Howard started when he suggested that police
officers should be covered by performance-related pay and fixed-term
contracts. Eventually the government backed down in the face of strong
opposition from the police force over the proposals, which were contained in
Sir Patrick Sheehy's report on police pay.
</TEXT>
