FT  22 SEP 94 / Unified accounts council proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the six leading bodies for accountants will today propose the
creation of a new supervisory and controlling council to govern the
profession.
Mr John Moore, president of the Chartered Association of Certified
Accountants, said: 'The General Accounting Council will provide a single,
prestigious and authoritative organisation to deal with those areas where
the profession has shared a responsibility to the public, and common
professional interests.'
The move follows a series of consultation meetings with chartered
association members to consider a merger plan put forward by the working
party of the Consultative Committee of Accountancy Bodies.
Only 19 per cent backed the CCAB scheme to create three institutes in
England and Wales, Scotland and Ireland.
Mr Moore said the chartered association plan would preserve the existing
bodies, but provide a new institution at the highest level to defend public
interest including that of the consumer.
Clark Whitehill, the 12th- largest accountancy firm in the UK, has announced
that it is to join the Horwath International network of accounting and
management consulting firms.
Clark Whitehill's move depends on Stoy Hayward moving from Horwath to BDO
Binder, the network currently represented in the UK by Binder Hamlyn. Binder
Hamlyn is expected to merge with Arthur Andersen.
