<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Accountants scorn takeover standard: Principles 'destroyed',
says Hundred Group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Accounting Standards Board was accused yesterday of 'destroying' one of
the basic principles of accounting after it issued two new standards
covering acquisitions and mergers.
The ASB, which decides how financial information is presented in the UK,
said the new rules 'call for a more objective, neutral and informative
approach' in accounting for business combinations.
The board said the new codes were designed to restrict the use of merger
accounting and outlaw abuses in the reporting of acquisitions which became
notorious during the climate of creative accounting in the late 1980s.
But the Hundred Group, which consists of the finance directors of companies
in the FT-SE 100 share index, described parts of the new standard on
acquisitions as 'completely illogical'.
Mr Nigel Stapleton, chief financial officer with Reed Elsevier and chairman
of the Hundred Group, said the standard 'destroys one of the basic
principles of accounting under which capital and revenue costs are kept
separate'.
The group calls for abuses to be dealt with by tightening existing
accounting standards and 'proper policing' by auditors 'not by distorting
basic accounting concepts'.
The dispute between the Hundred Group and the ASB marks the first open
disagreement between the standard-setters and industry since the board was
set up in 1990. In addition, the standard on acquisitions was passed by a
majority on the ASB of 7-1, marking only the second dissenting vote in its
history.
Mr Donald Main, a director of Forte, dissented from the majority view. He
said he agreed with many aspects of FRS 7 but hoped it would be reviewed
after a full debate on the general principles of accounting.
Sir David Tweedie, chairman of the ASB, said: 'The new standards favour
neither one side nor the other . . . and I believe that they will restore
much needed credibility in the reporting of acquisitions.'
Sir David said most professional accountancy bodies, auditors and financial
institutions had backed the standard. Reaction from companies had been 3-1
against.
The ASB's new standards, known as FRS (financial reporting standard) 6 and
7, are designed to stop the improper use of merger accounting to enhance
earnings and to curb the abuse of pre-acquisition provisions.
FRS 7 is designed to limit the costs that a company can meet through setting
up a reserve on its balance sheet when it buys another company.
In the past such devices have been used to stop costs appearing on the
profit-and-loss account and so boost headline profits. The new standards
will start next year and would normally not be reviewed for two to three
years.
Curbing creativity, Page 12
Editorial Comment, Page 23
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
