<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Jews win right to 'eruv' in London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
North London Jews will soon be able to visit friends on a sabbath and will
not have to leave their homes unlocked.
The first London 'eruv' - an area within which aspects of Jewish law are
relaxed - is to be established in Barnet in north London.
This follows a decision by the Department of the Environment to overturn
Barnet Borough Council's refusal to allow the eruv on planning grounds. The
council felt the poles and wires used for boundaries would be an eyesore in
the area, which embraces Hampstead Garden Suburb. However, a department
inspector, Mr David Rushby, decided after a public hearing last year that
the proposals would not seriously harm the character and appearance of the
area.
Jewish sabbath laws forbid carrying anything out of doors, even keys carried
in pockets. Pushing prams or wheelchairs is also prohibited.
Strict adherence to the law can be severely limiting for disabled people and
families with small children, who cannot attend synagogue services or visit
relatives on what is traditionally a family day. The law is waived within an
eruv.
Many Jewish communities around the world already have eruvs, but this the
first substantial one the United Synagogue Eruv Committee has managed to
establish in Britain.
The London eruv covers 11 square miles in the Golders Green and Hendon
areas. Barnet Borough Council will not appeal against the decision.
</TEXT>
