<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Overall accounts watchdog proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the six leading bodies for accountants will today propose the
creation of a new supervisory and controlling council for the profession.
Mr John Moore, president of the Chartered Association of Certified
Accountants, said: 'The General Accounting Council will provide a single,
prestigious and authoritative organisation to deal with those areas where
the profession has shared a responsibility to the public, and common
professional interests.'
The move follows a series of consultation meetings with chartered
association members in the current talks on the future structure of the
profession. Only 19 per cent backed a merger plan put forward by the working
party of the Consultative Committee of Accountancy Bodies, the existing
supervisory body for the profession. That proposal was to create three
institutes splitting the UK into three geographical areas.
Mr Moore said the consultation programme showed that the committee plan had
'too many drawbacks to be taken any further'.
Problems identified by the chartered association included the need to find a
common 'designation' for all accountants, how to serve the needs of students
overseas, and how to represent effectively the 200,000 accountants affected
in England and Wales.
The chartered association said that the proposal would protect its own core
values of open access and flexible entry.
</TEXT>
