<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / George shied away from July rate rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, nearly recommended a base
rate rise in late July, according to the minutes of his monetary meeting
that month with Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, which were released
yesterday.
The minutes relate to the meeting of July 28 when Mr George and Mr Clarke
decided to leave base rates unchanged. Base rates were increased from 5.25
per cent to 5.75 per cent after their next meeting on September 7.
In July, after reviewing a number of inflationary indicators such as
Confederation of British Industry surveys and input prices, Mr George said:
'It was possible to make a case that, to be on the safe side, there should
be a modest move to tighten policy now.'
He added, however, that 'there was not much danger of either the economy or
the emerging cost pressures running away at present'.
He also said there was 'a danger that a small move now would confuse rather
than reassure, and provoke an exaggeratedly nervous market reaction'.
The governor argued that 'the earlier a move was made the smaller the
adjustment would need to be. But in the current circumstances, it was
preferable for any move upwards to be to a level which would be a plausible
stopping point for a reasonable period.'
Some analysts yesterday interpreted this statement as indicating there would
not be a further increase in base rates for some time. But Mr Adrian Cooper,
UK economist at James Capel, said it was not inconsistent with a further
rise this year. Mr Roger Bootle, chief economist at Midland Global Markets,
cautioned against putting too much reliance on the governor's statement
since the view of the authorities had obviously been affected by data
published after the July meeting.
The minutes also show that, as late as the end of July, the chancellor was
fairly sceptical about the need for a rise in base rates. Mr Clarke said it
was important that 'any change in policy should be based on a balanced
assessment of all the evidence. There was a danger of trying to set a game
plan too far in advance and not looking at the actual evidence as it
unfolded.
'The latest data - particularly M4 and earnings - suggested a rise was not
required immediately,' he continued. 'Furthermore, the forecasts suggested
inflation might be even lower in the next few months.'
Nevertheless, Mr Clarke said: 'It remained true that, sooner or later,
interest rates might need to be raised.'
The minutes also indicate that the pace of economic growth may have been the
main reason why base rates were raised this month. In general discussion, it
was argued that 'as well as the absolute size of the output gap (the
difference between actual and potential output), it was possible that the
speed at which the output gap closed was an important determinant of
inflationary pressures'.
</TEXT>
