<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Ruling on Fayeds gives comfort to investigators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In rejecting the Fayed brothers' contention that the Department of Trade and
Industry inspectors' report into the 1985 takeover of House of Fraser
violated their human rights, the Strasbourg Human Rights Court has provided
a much needed crumb of comfort to the UK's system of company investigations.
Earlier this week, the European Commission of Human Rights cast a shadow
over company investigations by ruling that Mr Ernest Saunders, the former
Guinness chairman jailed for theft and false accounting after the company's
1986 takeover of Distillers, was denied a fair trial.
The commission said the use at his 1989 trial of answers given by Mr
Saunders under compulsion to DTI inspectors breached the European Convention
on Human Rights. If the full European Court of Human Rights eventually
upholds the commission's findings, the UK government may be forced to
rethink DTI investigations.
But yesterday the Strasbourg judges gave the company investigation procedure
a clean bill of health.
The Fayed brothers told the court in March there was no doubt that the
central conclusion of the DTI inspectors' report was that they were guilty
of dishonest misrepresentation.
The inspectors said the three brothers had misrepresented their origins,
wealth, business interests and resources to the trade and industry
secretary, the Office of Fair Trading, the press, the House of Fraser board
and shareholders and their own advisers prior to the takeover; and that
during the investigation they had knowingly submitted false evidence to the
inspectors. The Fayeds had always disputed these conclusions.
They said that in the eyes of the world, the report, which had been
published by the government, had the force of a judgment delivered after a
lengthy trial at which they had been convicted - except there had been no
trial and criminal charges had never been brought. The government had even
decided not to seek to have them disqualified as company directors.
They told the court that their right to a good reputation had been
drastically interfered with. The procedures governing DTI company
investigations afforded no safeguards for the rights of those under
investigation and they had no effective remedy against publication of a
condemnatory report and the damage it caused.
In short, they submitted, the denial of effective access to a domestic court
to defend their right to honour and reputation, and the denial of effective
domestic remedies to challenge the DTI inspectors' findings, amounted to a
breach of the convention.
The judges rejected the government's preliminary objection that the Fayeds
had failed to exhaust their domestic remedies. But they unanimously decided
there had been no violation of the Fayeds' human rights. The court said it
was satisfied the functions performed by the inspectors were essentially
investigative. The inspectors did not adjudicate. It could not therefore be
said the inspectors' inquiry had 'determined' the Fayeds' right to a good
reputation or had a decisive bearing on that right.
The right of access to a court to protect a civil right, guaranteed by the
convention, was not absolute, the judges said. It was subject to implied
limitations, which national authorities had a certain 'margin of
appreciation' in imposing, provided those limitations did not impair the
essence of the right, pursued a legitimate aim and were proportionate to the
achievement of that aim.
The judges said the underlying aim of the Companies Act investigation system
was the furtherance of the public interest in ensuring the proper conduct of
the affairs of public companies. The freedom of reporting enjoyed by DTI
inspectors as a result of being protected by privilege was also in the
public interest.
While the freedom to report was broad there were considerable safeguards
built into the procedure to ensure it was fair and that its findings were
reliable. Had it not been both fair and reliable the Fayeds would have had
the remedy of bringing a judicial review against the secretary of state or
the inspectors. But it was clear the Fayeds were informed of the information
required from them and were given every opportunity to respond to the
allegations against them and provide evidence.
The limits of acceptable criticism were wider for businessmen actively
involved in the affairs of large public companies than for private
individuals. The risk of some damage to reputation which could not be
compensated was inevitable if independent investigations were to have the
necessary freedom to report without fear, not only to the authorities but
also, in the final resort, to the public.
</TEXT>
