<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / DTI outlines view of Archer material
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, has opened up the
possibility of publishing the information disclosed to the inspectors in the
DTI report on Lord Archer's share orders in Anglia Television.
He said there was 'no legal barrier' to publishing the facts surrounding the
case given the consent of all those concerned.
Mr Alistair Darling, opposition City and financial services spokesman, said
all the information provided to the DTI inspectors about the affair should
now be made public.
But Mr Heseltine stressed that publication of the facts supplied to the
inspectors, without their judgment and assessment of these facts, would lead
to further media speculation as to why Lord Archer had bought the shares. He
added that he did not think that was a responsible exercise of his
functions.
In a letter to Mr Darling, Mr Heseltine wrote: 'Facts ascertained by
inspectors are inevitably the product of information provided by a variety
of witnesses, and of the inspectors' analysis, and judgment, on that
information.
'I recognise, however, that there would be no legal barrier, given the
consent of all concerned, to my publishing all the information provided to
the inspectors.'
After the DTI report Mr Heseltine decided that no action should be taken
against Lord Archer. His wife, Lady Archer, is a director of Anglia
Television.
Mr Darling said that now Lord Archer was back in the country there was
nothing to stop him making a full and frank statement.
He added: 'This matter is not going to go away. If there is no satisfactory
explanation I will raise the matter on the floor of the Commons when it
returns in October.'
</TEXT>
