<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Jordan set to quit as AEEU president
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Bill Jordan is likely to stand down as president of the AEEU engineering
union to take over as general secretary of the International Confederation
of Free Trade Unions, the biggest international union organisation with 174
affiliates in 124 countries.
Mr Jordan, 58, is not certain to get the job, but with backing from the US,
Germany and Japan, he is the favourite.
His main rival will be Mr Luis Anderson from Panama, head of the
confederation's Latin American region, who will have substantial backing in
the developing world.
If Mr Jordan does move to Brussels to run the confederation the way could be
open for Mr Jimmy Airlie, a former leader of the left in the engineering
section of the union, to take over as president.
However, there will also be strong pressure not to replace Mr Jordan. Since
the engineering and electricians' unions merged to form the AEEU it has had
an executive of more than 20 people plus two presidents and two general
secretaries.
For financial and political reasons the dominant group on the AEEU executive
may prefer to allow Mr Ken Jackson, current president of the electricians'
section, to become president of the whole union.
Mr Jordan, a powerful spokesman for rightwing craft trade unionism and a
lobbyist for the manufacturing industry, is regarded as one of the most able
of the older generation of British trade union leaders. He said yesterday
that taking over the confederation after the collapse of communism would be
a 'massive challenge'.
The current general secretary of the confederation, Mr Enzo Friso, from
Italy, is likely to stand down at the end of the year.
</TEXT>
