<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Ireland's only steel mill to close
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Directors of loss-making state-owned Irish Steel have recommended the
closure of its Cork-based steel plant - Ireland's only steel mill - which
would involve the loss of 520 jobs. The decision, taken at a board meeting
yesterday, follows the failure of the company to win agreement from its
craft unions on a survival plan which has been backed by the board, the
government, the Irish Congress of Trade Unions and other Irish Steel
workers. The survival plan was aimed at increasing flexibility among the
workforce but Irish Steel said yesterday that 'despite public statements it
is now clear that there is no basis for any agreement forthcoming' from the
craft unions. Mr Pat Dineen, Irish Steel chairman, and Mr Leslie Buckley,
acting chief executive, were due to meet Mr Ruairi Quinn, minister for
enterprise and employment, last night. If Mr Quinn accepts the
recommendation, a liquidator will be appointed.
</TEXT>
