<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 94 / Swedish socialists reject coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Ingvar Carlsson, Sweden's prime minister-elect, said yesterday he would
form a minority government following the victory of his Social Democratic
party in Sunday's elections. His announcement, after talks with other party
leaders, disappointed financial markets and business leaders who had hoped
for a majority coalition with the Liberal party.
However, the news was not unexpected and markets responded calmly. Bond
yields edged up and both the krona and share prices weakened slightly.
Standard &amp; Poor's, the US rating agency, reaffirmed its rating on Sweden's
long-term senior foreign currency debt at AA+.
Mr Carlsson said a minority government would be able to deal more
effectively with the country's large budget deficit and better assure the
country's accession to the European Union than a coalition. He stressed he
was confident of being able to work across party boundaries and gain support
for spending cuts and increased revenue worth SKr61bn (Pounds 5bn) to the
budget.
'The government which has the best chance to create broad agreement in the
Riksdag (parliament) is a Social Democratic government,' he said.
The Social Democrats hold 162 seats in the Riksdag, 13 short of a majority.
They are likely to rely on the former communist Left party or the Green
party on some issues and the Liberals or the Centre party, both members of
the outgoing centre-right government, on others. Any one party could provide
the necessary support for a majority.
Mr Bengt Westerberg, the Liberal party leader, resigned immediately after Mr
Carlsson's statement, criticising the Social Democratic leader for not
trying to build a coalition. He indicated during the election he would step
down if his party lost support - which it did - but it was clear he would
have been prepared to stay on to discuss a possible coalition.
Financial markets wanted a Social Democratic coalition with the Liberals
because they believed it would lead to tougher action to curb Sweden's
fast-growing debt and its budget deficit, which last year amounted to 13 per
cent of gross domestic product.
The yield on five-year Swedish bonds rose 6 basis points to 10.86
immediately after Mr Carlsson's statement.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
</CN>
