<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / International Company News: AEG to spin off drive system
unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Daimler-Benz's shrinking AEG subsidiary is to spin off its drive systems
operations into a joint venture with France's Cegelec, a member of the
Alcatel Alsthom group.
The loss-making German company will be the junior partner with a 49 per cent
stake in a business turning over DM1.4bn (Dollars 890m) annually - DM600m
from AEG - which will fall under management control of Cegelec.
The undertaking would be one of the world's leading suppliers of project and
drive systems with factories in four European countries, the US, Australia
and China, AEG said.
The move marks a further step in AEG's slimming and restructuring programme,
launched last December with the announcement of the sale of its household
appliances business to Electrolux, the Swedish multinational group.
Electrolux has since paid DM730m for the 80 per cent of the AEG operations
it did not own.
Other measures include the establishment of a 50:50 joint venture in
computer controls for plant and machinery with the French group Schneider.
Philips of the Netherlands bought the lighting technology business, and the
remnants of the Olympia office equipment division were sold to Hong Kong's
Elite group.
Meanwhile, AEG has taken control of most of the Daimler-Benz group's
microelectronics interests and absorbed the high-performance diesel engine
operations of MTU.
It is in the process of expanding its electronic mail-sorting equipment arm
through a Dollars 260m agreed takeover of ElectroCom, a Texas-based group.
Although AEG has forecast a further deficit this year after a DM1.2bn net
loss in 1993, improving world demand for industrial plant and electrical
components is expected to help it towards its goal of breaking even in 1995.
Its railways division, for example, yesterday forecast annual turnover would
rise almost a third to about DM3bn in the next five years due to DM5bn of
outstanding orders.
</TEXT>
