FT  21 SEP 94 / UK Company News: Strong emerging markets business lifts
Nelson Hurst
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A strong showing from its emerging market operations boosted half-year
pre-tax profits at Nelson Hurst, the insurance broker which came to the
market late last year, by 68 per cent from Pounds 2.61m to Pounds 4.38m.
Turnover for the six months to June 30 increased by 17 per cent to Pounds
21.5m (Pounds 18.4m), with the best performance - a 25 per cent increase -
coming from the group's middle and far eastern division. Total revenue was
ahead at Pounds 22.9m (Pounds 19.8m).
Mr David Woodward, chairman and chief executive, said: 'we have a presence
in all the big Asian business centres and have developed good relationships
with prominent local brokers.'
The group's link with Hopewell, the Hong Kong insurance group, was beginning
to show good returns and the recently opened Philippines office had good
potential, he said. Offices in Shanghai and Vietnam are planned for early
next year.
Turnover at the financial and reinsurance operations grew 15 per cent to
Pounds 8.69m (Pounds 7.57m), with a particularly strong showing from the
North American casualty insurance business.
London Overseas operations, which includes reinsurance of large construction
projects such as power stations, saw turnover grow 15 per cent to Pounds 7m
(Pounds 6.1m). However, aviation and marine insurance were difficult
markets.
The UK-based retail business was boosted by the joint venture with Price
Forbes Group, one of South Africa's leading insurance groups. Turnover
advanced 20 per cent to Pounds 1.94m.
Mr Woodward was confident on second half trading. 'We are seeing continued
revenue growth, both from our existing business and from new ventures. I am
quite bullish over our prospects.'
Earnings per share advanced from 5.1p to 6.4p. There is an interim dividend
of 2.2p.
