<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 94 / NFC forced to cancel third scrip dividend: Company will have
to pay shareholders another Pounds 545,000 in cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cancellation of one scrip dividend is unfortunate, but to do so for the
third time in a row - as NFC did yesterday - could appear to smack of
carelessness.
The cancellation follows the transport and logistics group's recent
indignity of losing its place in the FT-SE 100 index. NFC's shares have
underperformed the index by 40 per cent in the past year.
The value of the scrip alternative to NFC's second interim dividend, under
which investors could opt for shares in lieu of cash, was fixed at 198.2p in
July. By yesterday, after the departure of chief executive Mr Peter Sherlock
and a profits warning, the shares had fallen to 163p.
The cancellation will cost NFC Pounds 545,331, as 21,500 shareholders had
already opted to take up the shares. They will now receive the 1.5p per
share cash payment.
The two previous cancellations, in March and June, cost it close to Pounds
1.5m in cash, turning NFC's declining share price into a meaningful expense.
In the past year, Ladbroke Group and Albert Fisher Holdings have cancelled
scrip offerings, and volatile stock markets can clearly wreak unforeseeable
havoc on such offers.
In NFC's case, a weak market has been exacerbated by disappointment at the
aftermath of last year's Pounds 263m rights issue. High hopes of the
benefits of Mr Sherlock's rationalisation blueprint, that accompanied the
rights, have been dashed, and his departure raised further concerns over
NFC's strategic direction.
</TEXT>
